A Republican strategy to hinder the re-election of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center dismisses the latter as a myth and claims that voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the American states are responsible for the organisation of federal elections in the United States.
And along those same lines, a majority of U.S. governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread following the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, during the year 2011 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID, as well as proof of American citizenship.
These laws also shorten early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on polling day, and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to require it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
Therefore, the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo identification.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document such as a Social Security card.
In fact, some 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a state-issued photo ID.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identification.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25 percent of African-Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 percent of citizens over 65, and 20 percent of voters between 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters most likely to vote for Democratic candidates, cannot use their school-issued photo ID.
Moreover, those same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who tend to vote Republican to use documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers in 2011 supported laws that abolished voter registration on Election Day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a voter registration service.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favored shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, it was exactly the same.
They represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent only 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fervently opposed passing laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible to limit the damage to some extent.
For example, only 16 of 34 states passed laws requiring photo identification.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed, since it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
