The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed that this boson is involved in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what's more, it's the particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model -- our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it's not entirely clear that it's the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
And new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are needed to be absolutely sure.
Anyway, we assume it's the Higgs, because the chances of being wrong seem small.
There is, in this great world, a universal and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule, and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that it too has such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state".
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And then there's the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Lab's The Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", through which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs we might think.
In fact, if you can read this report, it is because of an extraordinarily common boson - the photon, or "particle of light", that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it disrupts the electromagnetic field in its immediate vicinity - somewhat like throwing a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing other than a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a bit like a frozen pond in which only a thick rock can slide across the surface.
A huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 17 miles [27 km] in circumference!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
The electromagnetic field analogy is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to a refrigerator door by itself.
And similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), don't.
But what "can" all this research "bring?" asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (SM), and further allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and predictions of the SM.
For their part, many fervently hope that they will, for the slightest difference could open the door to "new physics" that will plug certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another oops!).
But we haven't found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our daily lives are difficult to predict, but we do not think we are wrong in saying that it will have none.
To illustrate: In the early 1960's, laser pioneers in laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work would lead to.
They glimpsed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as noted by physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was considered more of a "laboratory apparatus".
Can you imagine that?
And furthermore, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light detector in 1969 in the course of his research in optics.
Although it was not his original intention, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, earning him the 2009 Nobel Prize in physics.
That doesn't mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but you never know...
Palliative care is the best way to die.
At its Dying With Dignity Commission, Quebec recently discussed the sensitive issue of end-of-life care.
The debate should resume soon while a draft law is being prepared.
Within this essential domain, however, much remains to be done.
Le Devoir tried to get a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr L. was living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year reprieve.
"They had given me five years to live, but I've been like this for seven", he says, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care centre in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for this", he continues.
The disease has taken its toll on him - a debilitating weakness that makes it impossible for him to go to the bathroom or even to eat by himself.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts help to eat.
Courageous, he even smiles and talks to strangers who give him attention, bring him medicine, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating", she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a cure.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois center.
To return to one's childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"That depends on the person's ability to accept that regression", he says.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the great moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses surrounding them no longer offer "curative" care.
89-year-old Mrs. A.'s greatest fear is to die "conscious and drowned".
But the illness has made him discover his children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no more desires left in this life", she says, before agreeing to have a mask put on to help her breathe.
And he hopes, in the coming days, a last visit of his son who lives in Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, she and a group of volunteers offer body care and help with food.
It's palliative care given when nothing else can be done.
To help make his death more comfortable.
In Quebec, we have one hospice bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little, since we all know we're all going to die eventually.
Here, life goes on under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the center.
Whether it's physical comfort, emotional comfort or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, depending on demand.
Diabetics no longer have their blood sugar checked.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served a beer to Mr. X, who died in the course of the night.
This morning, your son finished his beer at the deceased's feet.
"We help both patients and their loved ones", says Nathalie Savard, the care manager.
At the Victor-Gadbois centre, every day is different.
Next to a 94-year-old man savoring his last family reunion in the backyard, snuggled between his pillows as everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two children, having tried everything to survive.
"For the past six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under 45 years of age", worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent centre come from home and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
Some 77 percent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care - care designed to relieve suffering at the end of life, whether at home, in a hospital, or in a nursing home.
And a number of organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Centre and the Home Hospice of Greater Montreal, specialize almost exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this great relative deficiency in Quebec health care that makes many palliative care doctors fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by leading figures in palliative care, such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health-care system is not competent enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently", she relates, "I saw a patient spend 14 days in the ER in severe pain without any relief.
I'm afraid patients will want to die just because they don't get proper care".
And at the same time, many oncologists persist with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's hopes of survival were already at their lowest ebb when she left an exhausting chemotherapy treatment.
"When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop treatment, she told me that it made her sad that I wanted to stop fighting", she says.
"However, she had told me that there was nothing more to be done!"
There is no almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that about 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their demands once their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care in Greater Montreal, 8 percent of patients do not respond to pain medication.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is used to put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved disease is going to have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
Sick people who are not relieved all say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want euthanasia", but "I want relief".
