With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
This is in stark contrast to current monetary exchanges, which are based on central banks, identified transactions and processing burdens between parties.
Moreover, as is often the case in technologies, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency convertible to dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file sharing.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been logged thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a form of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars five months later, before returning today to around ten dollars (prices are censored on the page bitcoincharts.com).
It is nothing impressive if we compare it with world changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) became interested in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as "credits", used to advance in a video game and that can be earned by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously bookkeepers, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two electronic addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed using a double-key encryption system.
The network can then verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the changes of bitcoins are recorded in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction into that ledger.
This involves solving a mathematical challenge to the computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file fragmentation phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "chopping" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular fingerprint (plus leading zeros).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would remain orphaned, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is cut in half regularly, most likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed with each increase in computing power.
Life on the Net already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposit stolen.
"The flaw used does not affect the protocol itself", says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the potential for money laundering as a result of this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November the 'giant rebates' were launched.
"$30,000 changed hands", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on the currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as well as the transaction network.
Their system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, making them cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They simply supply an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement away from hierarchical systems towards more horizontal ones.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to catch on, but in 2013 there could be a change", he predicts.
In its report, the ECB also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in the event of this currency being successful.
