A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants him full powers, he decided to go for broke.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Only a week ago the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial entanglements.
This new initiative has only widened the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "betraying his word" and "trampling on the right".
Supporters say it is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short time span that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of recovering popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is causing havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote for him, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal was voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "either vote for my text or I keep full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange atmosphere that 85 members of this largely Islamist Constituent Assembly voted on the text yesterday.
The majority of the Liberals did not attend the meeting.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society followed suit.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitutes, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As was to be expected, the articles voted on were unanimous.
The commentators are amused, moreover, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all eyes, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that 'the principles of the Sharia constitute the main source of law'.
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that 'principles' could be replaced by 'norms', which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their good will and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The Liberals call it hypocrisy and see it as nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its conformity with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are also heightened by the fact that the next rector of the university would be considerably less moderate than the present one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulama but university graduates, some of them trained in the French system", explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity about Article 220, since the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
"We are specifically referring to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are civil judges competent to rule above all this".
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received much criticism concerning the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few in number compared to what they were under the previous regime.
Another point of conflict: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be banned, as requested by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concern about the text, which they considered to be a threat to freedom.
Blasphemy remains a criminal offence and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly for the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was scheduled to appear on television last night, demonstrations are expected this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern conveniences and unspoiled nature.
"AIF" identified the top five reasons to visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone entering this "baptismal font" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the site of Jesus' miracles - turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming a storm, and overflowing nets.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers walk here the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
It begins at the Fortress of Anthony, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the site of the crucifixion, to the Stone of Unction and to the burial place of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian Navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the site where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews, the Western Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their wishes, which will later come true.
Perform a vertical trip
The ruins of Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located on the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, can only those who are dedicated to climbing.
Others can reach this historic summit by cable car.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermon ski resort, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
There are bus services from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly dwelt on the mountain's summit.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of the most interesting are worth visiting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It preserves the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in caves in the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is worth a visit.
In its exhibition of paintings it has canvases of impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bath Al Basha, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea it is worth visiting the exclusive private Ralli Museum, where sculptures by Rodin and Dalí can be admired.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk into it and you're in total darkness.
The stars are shining.
And they play the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is mentioned as well.
Health and safety
The three main tourist areas in Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
Interestingly, they bathe in the Red Sea even in the winter months, when the water temperature does not drop below 70 degrees Fahrenheit [21°C] and the air warms up to 75 degrees [23°C].
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and bathing is available year-round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 meters below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustains even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to undergo courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing mud and fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia passed through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll along the narrow streets named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street of your "own" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries, to have their photographs taken.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the seat of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for nightly concerts and opera performances.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don't worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
Money for this trip is not advisable to carry in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shekels (currently 1-3$, 8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Traveling on any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transfer for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops close and public transportation is disrupted.
But on Sunday morning, a new workweek begins.
Many cafes, restaurants, and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, shellfish, fish without scales, and dishes that combine milk and meat.
There is a wide selection of beef and lamb dishes, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a variety of sauces, falafel - balls of ground chickpeas - fruits, and vegetables.
You don't see stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that "walk about as they please" in an impressive way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrs love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
Plus insurance, which comes out to $15 a day.
And renting a bicycle will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to tour the country and rest were citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, an amount that exceeds by 51% the same index of 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
"The great and powerful" will take you to Moscow: immigrants save for the language
While MPs and human rights defenders are discussing the consequences of the law on compulsory examination, scammers who trade in "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Each year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families back home.
From 1 December a law comes into force, according to which every migrant worker must take an examination to check his knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised in the Federal Migration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to pass the language examination, but also the Russian history and the basics of legislation examinations.
Knowledge of the language must also be confirmed for the purpose of obtaining and renewing a work permit.
Exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
People who managed to obtain their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Usefulness, necessity and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the tests in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the exam was supported by deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law came into force, managed many times to ask this question to the press: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for the immigrants themselves?
First of all, the representatives of the Immigration Service answer, this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the Russian Federal Migration Service's representation in Tajikistan.
The defence of your rights must begin before you leave.
Only an organised selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
Problems are faced by immigrants without a profession, education, those who do not know the language and do not pass the medical check.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev claims, the future immigrant will be doomed to encounter unscrupulous people who, under the guise of helping, will slip him a "paid trip" to a creepy, cramped hole, where he and dozens of others like him languish for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but upon arrival they are deceived, deprived of their passports, not paid the promised salaries", confirms the Head of the Labour Migration Directorate of Tajikistan's Migration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, little chief!
In the meantime, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia admit that not only do they not know the language of the country to which they intend to go, but they also have difficulty writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their own misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive a normal primary education.
This is because their families do not even have anything to feed the children, let alone clothe them, buy them shoes and school supplies.
Upon reaching adolescence, these youths venture out to work at the first opportunity.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, they recognize you.
"One feels humiliated and inferior".
However, when it comes to the language law, rights advocates make an important point.
The tests will be carried out only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have this status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or no strangers allowed".
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause is bureaucratic obstacles and language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a fake inscription can be made quickly and for only fifteen hundred rubles.
Employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea", Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Come on, don't be such a cheapskate, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be forged.
Several "fake" certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by officials of the Federal Migration Service.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came to the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, converge government officials and rights defenders.
Up to now, the authorities have been able to promise immigrant workers who failed the test the first time more time to study the basic language course.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
Ministry of Interior fails to take drastic measures against illegal arms trade
The percentage of crimes committed with registered weapons is quite low.
The Ministry of the Interior proposes to apply the law more rigidly in relation to owners of weapons for civilian use.
This is the government's reaction to the recent incidents: Shots fired during wedding celebrations in which fortunately there were no victims, and the massacre initiated by the Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinogradov, in which seven people lost their lives.
The police want to ban the use and possession of traumatic weapons in public places and raise the minimum age for obtaining a license to carry weapons from 18 years to 21 years.
