"For now, fooling the brain is not so easy"
The subject of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, is lately perceived normally mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, Google demonstrated a moving model at its annual conference, and then in November it emerged that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
However, a conversation with Izadi Sharamom, head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge laboratory, revealed that for the company's scientists, the glasses were already a thing of the past.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to extend the boundaries of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with a finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Even though Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We're trying to change this, working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
We must liberate the world from the computer to ours, the physical, make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognise not only the user but also the space around him.
Then we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think it's overrated?
- Of course it cannot be considered a panacea, it is pending to resolve the issue of privacy, since we do not always want others to know our actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not in single movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, gestures were captured not by the device's camera but by a wristband that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
Right now it's very large, but theoretically it can be scaled down to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can of soda?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be really hard to recognize.
- In other words, you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- Speaking of your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the issue is not megapixels, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this latter point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
So we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on the Z axis.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really poor, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, made a touch sensor with adjustable processing delay from 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
It would be very useful to me for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually the emitter of infrared rays and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually just a visible tuning fork sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog of Kinect, play with the curvature of camera placement and see how this would help determine three-dimensional position.
- As I recall, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not introduced its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that, from the point of view of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding up a smartphone in your hands, it's not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could move from glasses to smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, that's their strength (private things only you can see), but also their weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in mid-air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any mere mortal.
There's a problem with this idea that critics often point out: no tactile feedback!
My hands can't feel a thing!
What responses is your group preparing for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh irruption in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
It registers touch perfectly!
For example, the interference of several ultrasonic beams directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what you feel if someone is blowing on your fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this is also a promising direction.
- Have you tried tricking the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he seems like he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge that we will have to struggle with for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he is going to an open, almost endless space.
For now, fooling the brain is not so easy, there is still work to be done for many years.
That's what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, that a lot of things are in a state of full conception.
