Head of NKÚ: Inspection of "švarc" system failed to find guilty politician
In the area of public procurement, the Czech Republic has good inspectors and good legislation, although implementation is lagging.
This is stated by Miloslav Kala, vice-president of the Supreme Control Office (NKÚ) in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect", but its application must be correct.
Joint checks by Czech and German inspectors also lead to similar conclusions.
As an example of incorrect practice, he mentions Petr Nečas' attitude towards the system of being autonomous only on paper, which is known as the "švarc" system.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS (Civic Democratic Party) would not bother businessmen with inspectors.
"The law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, in that case, not even the president of the government can prevent the action of the office that has the obligation to carry out these controls or demand obligations", says Kala.
At the meeting of the Control Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke of the joint project between the Czech and German teams, in which the legislation on public procurement in the two countries was compared.
What is it, exactly?
This is a parallel control which we started to carry out about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regulates how public procurement should be organised, followed by national legislation and then national practice.
We have put it all together and, although the control has not yet been completed, we have obtained very interesting differences: generally speaking, the legislation in our country is 'stricter and more comprehensive', but the concrete practice in some parameters is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to incorporate ever stricter rules, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually contribute and what do you think are the conclusions?
It is precisely this kind of common control that could help us to stop investing efforts in making laws more concrete, reducing and improving limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
The economics of thrift mean getting the right thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest price) to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But the fact that we are reducing the ceiling on allocations does not mean that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much "paperwork", those who want to look for flaws in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You talk about our country's problems with the transfer of legislation regulating the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKÚ or is it organized differently?
As far as the offices are concerned, such as the NKÚ, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors) operates there, with an organization similar to ours, with a board as well, the only thing is that in its case it is structured somewhat differently, but in principle both offices are developing in parallel.
The powers are also to a certain extent similar, but in so far as Germany has a federal structure, the courts of auditors are even at this level.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, are controlled in Germany by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to say exactly where it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure, but, again, I don't like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries which we take as a model have to cope with a large number of problems.
Otherwise, it wouldn't do you any good to cooperate with our office, would it?
As far as the legislation in our country is concerned, what has the amendment to the law on public procurement meant for your Office?
Given the relatively short period of validity of this amendment, it has not yet been reflected in the monitoring procedures.
Since we are carrying out ex post controls, a certain delay is to be expected.
For the time being, it can be seen in the process of preparing for future controls: we have started a new tool for the 'detection of non-economic risks', through which we have passed almost 14 000 public tenders, which have been analysed.
Do you think that the adoption of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it means a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope it will be.
The problem that can arise is that the rules become 'tougher' and impossible to comply with.
Already under the previous legislation, the persons checked were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and any breach of the law on public procurement meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think this way.
