Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
They say the world is going to end in less than a month. What do you think?
It's just one of many scare stories we like to latch on to.
We in the band The Tap Tap rather like to joke about this and we like to say that we are the only band in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you are organizing a really original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain that to our readers?
It's a statewide charity event we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on December 20 at 9 pm, we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at about the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Whose idea was this?
Initially it was my idea, then we forged the project all together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, T-shirts, bags and original key chains against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The group The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, entitled "End of the world, canceled".
It's currently very popular on YouTube, will you be able to hear it at the benefit concerts?
Of course I do, and it'll just be the last one, well, as long as everything works out and the world doesn't end...
It will be sung by all performers at the same time in all three concerts.
The anthems will be linked together simultaneously by a special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the music video, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We work together even with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts...
We put all our efforts into participating in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the proceeds from the anti-apocalypse concerts be used for?
A equipment for the barrier-free educational centre Studeo, which we are completing for the sixth year in a row with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
The pupils of Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they carry out fun and interesting activities.
The pupils do not have sufficient financial means to pay the teachers and we make an effort to make it possible.
In the framework of the completion of the works at Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to make a programme that appeals to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague will perform Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
For more detailed information, please visit www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any similar "spectacular action" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of being in the United States, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have performed for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in electric wheelchairs, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which never ceases to amaze me.
Even in Moscow, where we have recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare the different attitudes of society towards disabled people and other aspects.
What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have seen that there is still a long way to go in the East.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, where it is still uncommon for a person to move around the city centre alone in an electric wheelchair.
As common as it is, for example, to give preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, it is not there.
Fortunately, a civil association has been set up to address the problems of people with disabilities.
In what respects should we take example from more advanced countries?
There's a lot of ways we're behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people directly affected.
In London and in Madrid it is very normal for people with severe disabilities to move on their own in public and to be able to go to the toilet, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of disabled people to participate actively in social life, in this respect, with The Tap Tap we are a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes that eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, everything will really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The group Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered as an educator in Jedličkův ústav, where I had many young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I'm a musician, I play, among other things, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a colleague.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughter).
However, the popularity didn't come until these last few years, or am I wrong?
It's true that connecting with famous singers and also actively working to promote the group helped us a lot.
We came to the conclusion that the work that is not seen, is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to European Union aid, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that something can be done differently.
Show business is full of things that look alike.
It is logical, in its own way, that everything new is received with caution and takes a long time to be accepted.
There are few things more extraordinary, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because disabled people are not abandoned beings who suffer and for whom we should have compassion.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes right for people with disabilities, then it's not just progress for them, but for the whole society.
Did it help that you're a demanding boss, as many people describe you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many respects and demand a certain amount of discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds and when they find out they have to go for two days to rehearse, go to the pre-test and spend a lot of time traveling and in concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
Currently the group The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there at the beginning of 1998?
There is only one, Lada Angelovic.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't help it.
Whoever has the will and desire will always find the doors open
