Poland and the cosmos.
At last week's meeting of ministers from the European Space Agency countries, Poland was accepted as ESA's 12th member - the second ESA member from the former Eastern bloc after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began intensive cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already involved in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented his ideas on the pioneering study 'Introduction to Cosmonautics'.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent, and years later Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In the year 1934 Šternfeld obtained in France the prize Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a rocket-powered train was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and neither are the details of the project known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used to start the dresina or to brake it.
The information about this dresina is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to focus on missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfkem and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzycki.
From the material preserved, it is clear that the research reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was discontinued.
In the year 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of rocket engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the journal Problemy the society is first referred to with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
One of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to become part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became the vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the sounding rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket on which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first flown on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, construction of the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów Desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket under development was to be the subject of real scientific study.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32,5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum apogee in all three types was 37 km (23 mi).
Between the years 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg up to 60 km altitude.
Later the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Mention should also be made of Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the space research on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the problem from a wider angle.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of more economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
This is a situation in which the manufacturer, by importing cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to this end 'causes a fall' in the competitor's price with the aim of taking over most of the market and thereby increasing his profit margin.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing altogether.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and is therefore not responsible for the unemployment it creates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
All this has led to a complete lack of interest on the part of businessmen in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their quest for profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations in certain economies in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments put private capital at the disposal of their own population without regard to social decline.
This is particularly evident in changes in existing legislation.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially as regards wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of financial obligation in the case of longterm unemployment and, on the other, through the restricted right of employees to employment rights.
The result is growing poverty along with widening gaps between rich and poor.
For a number of years now, there have been food distribution points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves by their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is now close to one million.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed on such a low salary that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary for survival.
A scandal of this kind was made public in connection with the situation of auxiliary staff in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of practically all the southern EU countries are undoubtedly leading to the same situation: people, pressured by a precipitous decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live on a miserable wage at the margins of society, in the hope that one day private investment capital will reach the country.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty either passes from one country to another or never arrives at all, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny fraction of a European wage.
This also affects the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim ad nauseam that the state should not provide capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Secondly, we must ask ourselves whether private capital is not selfishly influencing the political process and, therefore, the entire state.
In this case the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation which manifests itself in corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation which is almost universally reprehensible but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, lacking financial resources, entrust the drafting of legislation to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
Such bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as is proclaimed in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from powerful financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation like that described by Appiános in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been disintegrating and the administrations were occupied by force".
In exchange for bribes, ill-gotten favors and help in financing stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unimpeded and people went to the polls with a pre-arranged vote... "there were no people with character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "It began to be seriously talked about that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"... Although Appiános thought of Pompeia, Caesar rose to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that today's society is based on reckless preferences for individual gain without regard for common interests.
Private capital is not capable, in its essence, of understanding and claiming the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as it was then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without any effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the present situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems in favour of a liberal type of democracy as a definite pause, waiting for the next blow.
The truly devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, the social and humanitarian catastrophes we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them in ancient and more recent history.
The suspension of the law on public procurement is not the solution, at least not in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the Czech government will be forced to continue to seek other ways of reducing the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution lies in concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
