The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which every year presents a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has now decided to announce the contest on "the most absurd regulation or ideas from the EU workshop".
"It occurred to us after the last event, the EU is planning to approve a 40% quota of women in management positions in large European companies", explained Právo Patrik Nacher, the organiser of the survey.
Among the absurdities listed is, for example, the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify insurance policies for men and women.
Until now, women have benefited from better prices in life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk.
"Other amazing ideas from the EU workshop can be proposed by people until the end of this year".
The election will take place at the end of February 2013", Nacher reported.
Among the controversial EU regulations are, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel which, as a result, damages the environment; another prohibition is the use of lifelong mercury thermometers just because they contain a small amount of a dangerous substance or the directive shades the size of hens' cages, which has contributed to the considerable increase in the price of eggs this year.
The de facto ban on the use of the term 'butter spread' and the withdrawal of the classic light bulb from shops have been criticised.
A quality banana should be 14 centimeters long.
The Union apparatus often takes such decisions under pressure from one or other commercial or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (the Czech Republic, even with the threat of veto, claims the demands of its banks).
The interests of a lobby were behind the request, for example, that the highest quality bananas in the EU should be at least 14 centimetres long and must not have 'abnormal curves'.
The European Commission defended itself by saying that it was only seeking to harmonize national standards which had not been harmonized to date and which only complicated their marketing.
Rules referring to fruit and vegetables in the EU, despite opposition from some states, have been softened on the grounds that the existing directive leads to food waste.
The winning candidate in the survey could be last year's EU requirement that inflatable balloons placed on the market carry a mandatory warning that children under the age of 8 are not allowed to inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU was referring here to an American study which showed that balloons are the main cause of children's death by suffocation when it comes to toys.
A similar restriction applies to the use of mothballs by children up to 14 years of age.
