He argued that our country produced a lot of cereals and, as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full warehouses and had to export.
According to Palas, since the Czech Republic is far from seaports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
In the end, the European Commission was willing to help the Czech Republic and organised a public tender for the purchase of cereals from landlocked countries.
The subsidy to receive a grant was proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry for Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU).
