Architecture studio MVRDV proves that real adventures are not only in the head - on the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "book mountain" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "Besides, the building is beautiful".
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
No one goes into those old-fashioned libraries for fun, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town on the outskirts of Rotterdam hardly worth a quick visit, has the dubious honour of having set a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to make a contribution to the general culture by copying the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so policy makers decided that there was only one way to improve statistics: build a library!
Winy Maas of the Dutch architectural firm MVRDV, a master of the art of bar graphs and responsible for funny yet cynical buildings, approached the subject with his usual serenity and attended the competition presentation in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in bewilderment and shrugged their shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words:
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books in Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'".
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain rises in its intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of apartment buildings and townhouses.
At the beginning of November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the 'Dutch National Wood Award 2012'.
In this way, the small town with no history, which until now had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white façade one would rather intuit a dairy, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that this is a paradise of books under a cheese grater.
True, there is an elevator that takes us right into the heart of this mountain range, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, preferring instead to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy on the eye, the annealed brick floor and elegant lampposts unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
Looking up, you can see park benches, dogs, and boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Usually the bookshelves are arranged along the facade, and in the middle there is a large dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
What we've done is we've turned the classic spatial configuration upside down and taken the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves, which serve as wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the town of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a Frisian farm, we stumbled upon the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, a plastic mesh a few millimetres thick has been used as a support for the roots of crops.
It's a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts for two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates four centimeters thick.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes colour into a dark, homogeneous and durable material that smells like a mixture of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 1,600 feet [500 m] around the mountain, we are rewarded with not only a fantastic view of the city but also delicious Dutch croquettes and ficus plants in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology", says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is provided by geothermal energy.
Even though the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
Huge wooden trellises across the glass facade provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is up to the blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the sceptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, also visited the library and described the 'Boekenberg' as the 'late soul' of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration which took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the town were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
The aim is to fill the gaps in a library which does not yet have a complete archive, but which currently holds 70,000 items.
The concept has taken hold.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative all the inhabitants now have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved a great deal of success in that key discipline which in specialist jargon is known as 'identity creation'.
The town of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
Regardless of how young and uneducated he may be.
At last a starting point to shape their identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer state status at the United Nations.
However, Berlin ultimately abstained.
What's wrong with that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the country's special relationship with Israel, Germany has to be careful.
But at the same time I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear stand on important international issues?
Yes, that's right, I did.
This is because it is now reorienting its foreign policy away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and towards a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that the Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they have already started down the road to a 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What exactly does a 'normal' foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy which, when national interests are at stake, is prepared to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China and the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other great powers and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance on the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
That is why it must be careful not to alienate Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not attach too much importance to it because it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by abstaining on important decisions like the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been as drastic a break as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps this has earned Germany a certain amount of respect.
After all, all this has only demonstrated that it is a country which is taken seriously as an international player and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, was clearly in favour of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic policy.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding for the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is obvious that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I believe that the real difference of opinion is not as great as is claimed.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand with the position of its main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
They therefore have no possibility of being part of a higher authority, but must push things forward from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in future Germany will play a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European attitude.
Of course this is not at all easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship it has with Israel.
This has always been a touchy subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player and does it really want to play a leading role?
Or do you still find it difficult to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet got used to it, it is always somewhat uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it still finds it difficult to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany is positioned as a major player, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and that is that nobody wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Seen in this light, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You have to show an open attitude to different neighbours and opinions and that is not easy.
The United States' influence on European politics is diminishing, but the EU is not filling the gap. Who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to assume a more prominent role.
Even if you don't like it, if you find it distasteful or if it makes you an even more unpopular people, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a fellow at the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
This name hides a name officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be proved right.
"Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in trademark infringement in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes across my desk.
Copycats simply add a couple of letters so they can register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and Prada is registered as Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copying in the same way, as has happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are multi-storey department stores devoted exclusively to the sale of counterfeit goods.
However, Pattloch's cases are different: on behalf of his clients, he fights against the trademark office officially granting Chinese companies the right to profit from a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "caught" a rich man.
The Chinese authorities don't feel guilty
"It's bad for business, we have to fight it", Pattloch demands.
