Facts About Sexually Transmitted Diseases
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Lice and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur more often in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five cases of syphilis in Germany are caused by sexual contact between men.
For heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomoniasis, human papillomavirus, candidiasis, and gonorrhea.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydial infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections occur among young people aged 15 to 25.
In our country, human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are notifiable.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
Approximately 2,700 cases were registered in 2011.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, abdominal pain, and blisters or warts.
They often cause no pain or other symptoms and so go undetected.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100 percent protection.
Some sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through infections from dirt and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical checkups, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any long-term consequences avoided.
