A trip through the Talysh Mountains can be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus hurtles along the winding road past forested hills, fast-flowing rivers, and the simple homes of local farmers.
Everything is green and juicy, you might even think you're in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan, just a few miles from the Iranian border.
Here live the "talyshi", a people about whom not much is known, apart from the fact that they are fluent in Persian and Azeri and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts architecture that is perhaps too massive, designed in the Soviet era, and doesn't quite seem to fit into such a picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists rarely come here, as the road from Azerbaijan's capital, Baku, is too rough.
It takes eight hours to travel the 200 miles [323 km] between the two towns because the road is one-way.
The country's staggering oil wealth from the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will hold the Festival of the oldest people in the world", Fatulayeva notes.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one in the world.
Here documented are the lives of eight dozen local talishis who are over 100 years old, Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
One of his sons died at the age of 136
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the shepherd Şirali Müslümov, who appears to have lived for 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate to prove it.
And if we take into account that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov's age is quite suspicious.
"He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973", Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children. Apparently he still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Has Şirali Müslümov then been wrong about his age by a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, Germany, has also heard of this Central Asian's advanced age.
"In some regions of China, Japan or the Hunza valley in Pakistan there are also very old people", says Scholz, "even in Sardinia there are many older men".
Due to the lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific proof of age; especially when there is also no civil registration.
