But this is not so, according to Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book Boredom: A Lively History, published in 2011 by Yale University Press.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history", he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century A.D.
We also need to rethink how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways", says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing published research and presenting the idea to a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but not being able, to participate in a fulfilling activity".
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that a person doesn't do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "an altered attention process, associated with low mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can sound an awful lot like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that while they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as environmental or worldly, whereas people who are depressed see the problem as their own.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what's really happening to us is we're having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened to an unrelated television program in the next room at full volume, others listened with the volume turned down so that it was barely audible, while the third group heard no audio at all.
The group that listened to the program with the volume turned down showed more boredom than the other two groups; they had trouble concentrating, but they weren't sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you're trying to focus on a difficult or interesting task, distraction can lead to boredom", said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
"On the other hand, when you are doing something boring, such as detecting defective parts on a production line, distracting music can help you not to get bored".
"In fact, we now know that moving or doodling, actions often misinterpreted as signs of boredom, can actually help combat it by making that person more physically alert".
"Research shows that children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still", says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: a delayed plane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring movie.
But some people are more prone to boredom than others.
To help measure it, some researchers in the 1980's developed a "boredom-tendency scale".
The scale includes questions such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things I'm interested in that I don't have time to do everything".
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that by using such scales, researchers have found that boys tend to be bored more often than girls, and they need more external stimulation and more variety.
But by and large, teenagers are a fairly easily bored group.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search engine.
It found that 32 percent of teenagers said they were bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of the parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether today's boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But what she did know, she said, was that "adolescence is a time of peak boredom", largely because both children and teenagers are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my original question: Is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it's not, because taken to the extreme, it can expose us to absurd physical risks, like gambling or falling into substance abuse as a way to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this question for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's appropriate.
If you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short run, but not in the long run.
"So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he hasn't learned to entertain himself or to pace himself", says Professor Fenske.
And "this ability to dose oneself applies to other situations", he says.
Not only does your child learn to entertain himself but he learns to exercise better self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
At the same time, we should not be overly critical of him.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees with me.
"In our view, we need to be more bored, but boredom is too distressing and disturbing a desire to relate to anything worthwhile", he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy some downtime.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated", he says, "it's hard to find ways to focus when the noise stops".
