The toughest job in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their job is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it must descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies on contact with the air.
After tearing out large lumps of sulfur, weighing up to 150 pounds [70 kg], he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets over steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, but it takes the exhausted porters more than 40 minutes to ascend at a snail's pace, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall over the precipice.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who tumbled from the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur they extract
Once at the top, they push their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, wearily carrying their heavy baskets, walk two miles [3 km] to the scales that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 6,000 feet [1,850 m].
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (US$0.70) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widely used in everyday life to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we normally carry about 150 pounds [70 kg], we make about 46,000 rupees [$3, U.S.] per trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
He spends three hours on each and ends up crushed, but he is allowed to collect 138,000 rupees (US$11.50) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a pittance for such inhuman effort, it is triple what I would earn in the field.
"The daily wage of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros) ", explains the porter, who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cutting was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as forceful as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, shortness of breath, constant cough and irritation of the eyes from toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been risking his skin for three years in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He suffers from asthma, breathing difficulties, a persistent cough, and irritation of the eyes from the volcano's toxic gases.
It's the price you have to pay to achieve your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French", he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this nice, intelligent young man could be a tour guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur keeps pouring down at night, when its distinctive yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminated by a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he has bought with his own money.
Some 400 porters carry baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the crater floor
Despite its huge profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs, nor does it supply any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and by weight.
In fact, they do not even see a fraction of the 30,000 rupees (US$2.50) per camera surcharge, along with the 15,000 rupees (US$1.50) entrance fee, that park rangers charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for beasts and not for people", protests Madrusin, a stocky 42-year-old porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, she assures that she will endure working "all that she can" because she needs the money to educate her three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns coming out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of serious illness - apart, of course, from their usual respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain, and sore shoulders, which have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his colleagues extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life", Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five sons, the eldest, aged 30, also works hauling sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest jobs in the world: that done by the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
