A lot of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do the most creative thing we can to solve this problem, which is write a rap?
1.2 children
The one not taking it so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leaders and strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replacement rate - was 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it is because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
"This has enabled people to have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family", he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increased singleness, and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decline in Singapore's birth rate.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to cope with population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, websites abound with thinly disguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
Increased immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore's ruling party experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unintended Consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as 'shoe boxes', that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a surface area of 46 square metres and have been very successful in sales.
However, there is concern that they may promote a single-person lifestyle and discourage developers from building large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" are selling much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that the units sell out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, it admits that the new rules give clearer guidance to developers, who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too much stress.
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans who work in the downtown financial district, it seems they won't have much effect.
"People are very stressed, housing is expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off", says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time", says another young man in his 20's.
Men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons for not having children.
So, as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the final say.
Private off-line is private online.
It's called privacy.
According to the Diccionario de la Real Academia Española (Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy), it is the quality of being private or "the sphere of private life that has the right to be protected from any intrusion".
What's private to a 16-year-old?
How do you apply this definition in your daily life and on social media?
Do you understand the dangers of posting things online that you would not share offline?
elPeriódico interviewed five boys between ten and 15 years old, frequent users of the network.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very mine", on a personal level, and "in the password and username", when applied to social networks.
"I wouldn't post my deepest secrets", says ten-year-old Jorge, as he tries to explain the meaning of private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail, and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know them, but not everybody", she says.
On FB I upload pretty pictures or games.
I also entertain my acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't of me, or someone making a fool of themselves", he says.
The child recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene pictures, pictures of naked people, pictures of crimes, or to write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother's in on it, she's got a key to one of the accounts.
I opened Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just upload them", he adds.
"Social networking is fun, and I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly", she says.
He does not hesitate to say that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
I wouldn't listen to anyone who recommended a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, in the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people added to his friends list.
"It doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, music for example", he says.
According to the boy, no one has ever made a pass at him or asked for his home address or phone number.
"If I'm pressured or demanded, I just take it out of my account", he admits.
José became a follower of Ask, after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to experiences of what is now known as cyberbullying.
An acquaintance of a friend of mine was being extorted on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who I was", she says.
The victim, according to Jose, never closed the account.
"He just put privacy in it".
It then explains a series of steps to set up the account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yes, he would, if he didn't like me or wanted to.
"Even though I know that's cyberbullying", she says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English and a graduate in Education and Learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a means of searching for information, but with the emergence of these sites the rules of the game have changed", he says.
Porras points out that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in Pedagogy from Yale University and is the author of Natives and Digital Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are they, the children and young people who were born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them, while we are still learning", he says.
He comments that the subject is complex, "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion about what should or should not be disseminated, published or said at an age that maturity does not allow for that".
"Also, be selective if your main concern is to be popular, to have thousands of friends regardless of the consequences".
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is through thought-provoking questions.
"Telling them not to is not helpful", she adds.
Next, Porras lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like to have a picture of yourself published like the one you posted of a friend?
Do you know what others publish about you?
When you tag photos from parties, do you ask other people's permission to tag them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing at all times?
Another point is to make them see that they should act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, one acts with respect, morality and other principles, the same should be in social networks", he says.
Monitoring and surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, elementary-school teacher, and educational consultant, says that it is essential for parents to read social networking policies carefully.
By understanding each of these points, parents have a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
"For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or posted", he says.
According to Guardia, a key lesson is to remind children "not to talk to strangers".
Unasur summit ends without Lima declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without making public the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders.
Efe tried on several occasions to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency initially indicated that they would deliver it after the closing, but later affirmed that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the governments of Unasur attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents attending, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the III Summit South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that had previously been announced was not disseminated.
On the official website of ASPA it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that transmission systems were secured for all journalists but limited information gathering as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences that today we are taking to this international court", said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, the peaceful solution of controversies, treaties and international courts", added Piñera, and greeted with a handshake to Humala, along with the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The President read out the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and lines of action were set for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are extending the agreements on residence".
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-cost Internet access in all corners of South America, and joint and efficient response to natural disaster risks".
MEPs in the committee are calling on the Commission and the Member States to take the necessary measures to ensure that the EU's financial interests are taken into account.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", said the Peruvian president in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
'We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations', from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and of good neighbourly relations, was another issue highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully deal with the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) it is possible that I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell him that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the bloc's defense ministers previously met to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
