AIDS deaths today are caused by late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he tested positive for AIDS.
"It was like a bomb dropped on me", he says, recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make "a little softer", with no apparent success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take matters into his own hands and began to learn about his illness - so much so that he celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 90s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying good-bye to him "because he had a cut".
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
Yet, unaware of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, "exhausted" their immune systems, and become victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, at least of the first reported cases, "the great achievement means at this time that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population, is exactly the same", said the head of the HIV Unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after referring that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and expert in HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of affectation to the immune system that patients present at the beginning of the diagnosis, with better expectation for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years when they report 500 CD4.
In simple terms, this means that whoever is diagnosed HIV positive at the age of 25, under these terms "as long as he stays in control he can live without problems until he is 75 years old", explained the interviewee.
To measure this progress, it should be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
While mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS dropped from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
Only in Jalisco 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths until May of this year; however, it is assured that there is universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why do people keep dying?
- It seems to me that the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I visualize it, that's how it happened to us in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we haven't had a shortage of drugs. The problem is that patients arrive very advanced because they don't know their infection status, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He gave a resounding figure: "Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection. What needs to be done to have a greater impact on global mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, therefore, to offer screening tests massively, to all the people who require it".
Specialists and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to be tested at a private laboratory, only motivated because a friend had done so and, despite his young age, was already in the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, I might as well blow my brains out three times a week", they say not in my case.
The change was for the better. I'm eating right, exercising, taking my meds.
To date, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sexual life, but I am also responsible, I take care of myself and the other person", said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate experience with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate those who are afraid today, on World AIDS Day.
Get tested, if you were at risk, the sooner you know if you are HIV positive, the better and if you already have the diagnosis, learn that you can live like anyone else, being responsible.
That, his message, sums up the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter.
