Ratified by a court of appeals of the United States a ruling that does not recognize the restructuring of the debt of the Vitro Group achieved via a commercial competition in Mexico, the scenario sets a disastrous precedent for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It would therefore seem that the procedures for guaranteeing the survival of firms permitted by Mexican law are not valid in the country of the stars and stripes, contrary to international conventions.
In practical terms, the backing given to the ruling handed down on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale of the bankruptcy court for the northern district of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenceless against the possibility of seizure of their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the ruling opens the door for Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to go to the U.S. Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies.
At the outset, while the judge in the case points out that creditors must be governed by the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says that the principal procedure is the Mexican bankruptcy.
The first point would involve ignoring international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law on the Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created to that end, with the American Law Institute serving as arbiter.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the inter-company vote, recognised in the critical mass of the tender, the debts of Vitro's subsidiaries to their parent company would not have achieved the majority required to approve the restructuring.
However, the possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
