They start a course that explores the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible lure: The end of the Mayan Calendar's "long countdown" on December 21, which many people have seized upon as proof that the world is coming to an end.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited her in the next couple of months: the cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called "debt Armageddon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end-times theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charmé told students at Rutgers University-Camden, New Jersey, this week.
If you look at what's been happening in the world today as if we're 30 days in and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember, bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mindset.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, adjunct professor Barry Vacker is teaching a course called "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time", he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month students analyzed movies with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
"I have tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible and impossible", said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, simply titled "The End of the World".
"We don't add '2012' because we always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end", Restall said.
Despite the "imminent ruin", students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night the world is supposed to end", Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It saturated in two hours", Restall said of his course for high-achieving students, which filled with 35 students.
We got emails for weeks and weeks before the semester started, from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, say the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old Religion and Sociology major from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
And the apocalyptic mindset, secular or religious, is just a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I had never heard of a class that could teach that", he said.
I enjoy it.
But not a single student interviewed - much less a teacher - said that he believed in the December 21 expiration date.
"Our first project was about the Mayan prophecy and we kind of debunked it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple and from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it is just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, going back several centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in these speculations.
"In other places people don't think about this", he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching courses in the Philippines this year, was quick to respond to a question about whether he knew of any "end of the world" courses there.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world", he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that many doomsdays have been talked about over the years, and he said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to attend "end of the world" parties.
"Maybe I'll call some friends to laugh with me", said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
